main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11551743921986544093504589603082880894504"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834832?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2022 年，新墨西哥州阿尔伯克基使命成就与成功特许学校的三年级学生。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿尔伯克基日报/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11551743921986544093504589603082880894504"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">内奥米·谢弗·莱利</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 13 日下午 3:18 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-death-of-public-school-review-find-a-place-to-learn-4817d47c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>什么是公立学校？它是一个由公众付费的机构吗？一名由政府雇员组成的人员？一个教授公开认可的课程的学校？一个能够教育广大公众儿童的学校？在《公立学校之死》一书的作者卡拉·菲茨帕特里克看来，它具备所有这些品质，而且确实如此。不少家长不同意，或者对公立学校的想法完全不再抱有希望，这让她感到担忧。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a74aaa7c-35f1-4344-b5a3-aafc1dd7194d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>菲茨帕特里克女士是一名资深记者，也是教育网站 Chalkbeat 的编辑，对于她来说，公立学校的消亡——或者至少是衰落——主要归因于保守派，正如她的副标题所言，他们“赢得了教育领域的战争”。美国。”在她看来，他们通过支持择校、学校券和特许学校来推进他们的进攻。</p><p>菲茨帕特里克女士对这些另类政策和制度的不太同情的历史始于 20 世纪 50 年代的种族隔离主义者。她展示了民权时代反对种族融合的人们如何支持父母应该选择孩子的学校的想法——在那个时代，目标是避免黑人孩子。她指出，在<em>布朗诉教育委员会案</em>（1954 年最高法院裁决废除学校种族隔离）的四年内，一些南方州“在必要时采取措施放弃公立学校”，并“设立了助学金，供学生用来支付私立学校的学费”。学校。”菲茨帕特里克女士表示，此类举措是“创建学校学券制度的第一步”，类似于米尔顿·弗里德曼 (Milton Friedman) 在 1955 年特别提出的制度。</p><p>尽管菲茨帕特里克女士并没有指责弗里德曼与南方人有相同的动机——她引用了他的话说，他鄙视种族隔离和种族偏见——但她说，他对代金券的看法似乎“要么天真，要么故意无视南方的种族压迫”。 ”。弗里德曼认为，私人系统——用代金券帮助家庭支付学费——将提供一系列自愿协会：纯白人学校、纯黑人学校和混血学校。他说，反对种族偏见的人不应该强迫父母把孩子送到一种或另一种种族，而应该“努力说服别人接受他们的观点”。如果他们成功了，“混合学校的发展将以牺牲非混合学校为代价，并且逐步过渡将会发生。”</p><p>很难说这样的想法是否幼稚。正如菲茨帕特里克先生似乎暗示的那样，这当然不是无知或恶意的。当时，有专门针对黑人学生的高质量机构，特别是慈善家朱利叶斯·罗森瓦尔德 (Julius Rosenwald) 在 20 世纪头几十年在南方建立的罗森瓦尔德学校 (Rosenwald school)。如果黑人家长能够获得支持他们所需的代金券，这样的学校很可能会继续蓬勃发展。</p><p>当然，人们支持择校的原因不止一个。有些人赞成有限政府，认为在儿童教育方面，国家应该屈服于父母的偏好。一些人赞成为宗教学校提供更多资源。马凯特大学耶稣会教授维吉尔·布鲁姆 (Virgil Blum) 在 20 世纪 50 年代末写了一篇文章，呼吁“在不强制服从的情况下提供教育福利”，他的意思是，孩子们不应因为缺乏资金而被拒绝进入公立或私立学校。在某种程度上，他想让天主教学校系统成为公立学校的更强大的替代品，公立学校有时是由不容忍宗教异见的新教徒开办的。</p><p>学校选择或学券——或者特许学校（特许学校在政府限制和教师工会规则之外运作，同时接受公共资金）所带来的教育有多好？菲茨帕特里克女士说，目前还没有定论。她引用了各种研究，得出了不同的结论。她没有提到就读 Success Academy 的学生考试成绩得到了天文数字般的提高。 Success Academy 是纽约市特许学校网络，成立于 2006 年，目前为 20,000 多名 K-12 年级的学生提供服务。</p><p>关于教育的争论可能会造成奇怪的同床异梦。菲茨帕特里克女士讲述了 20 世纪 90 年代支持私立学校学券的密尔沃基黑人民主党议员波莉·威廉姆斯 (Polly Williams) 与威斯康星州白人共和党州长汤米·汤普森 (Tommy Thompson) 结盟的故事。在帮助实施该国第一个代金券计划后，威廉姆斯转向汤普森，因为他希望代金券能够普及，而她希望这些代金券只提供给穷人。</p><p>菲茨帕特里克女士似乎觉得，倾向民主党的黑人家长正在被倾向共和党的白人倡导者玩弄，他们推动公立学校的替代方案。这些倡导者表示，他们关心市中心儿童的最大利益——他们的公立学校往往很糟糕——但菲茨帕特里克女士暗示，他们确实想进行宗教灌输（通过教会规定的课程），或者通过最终私有化来赚钱。公立学校。她毫不客气地形容克林特·博利克（Clint Bolick）——他是许多第一批学券案件的辩护人——“永远不会错过一个良好的公共关系机会”。</p><p>对于那些似乎倾向于质疑那些支持择校的人的动机的人来说，菲茨帕特里克女士似乎对其他人反对的原因不太感兴趣。从比尔·克林顿到巴拉克·奥巴马等民主党人最初支持特许学校和学校选择，但当教师工会威胁撤回他们的政治支持时，他们就放弃了。</p><p>那么，遗憾的是，除了引言中的几句话外，菲茨帕特里克女士的分析到了 2019 年就结束了。2020-21 年的大流行向来自不同地理区域和政治背景的家长暴露了公立学校的缺陷。效忠，尤其是当老师不听话，导致孩子们无法上学并导致他们落后时。过去两年，至少有五个州通过了全民学校选择。如果菲茨帕特里克女士之前认为公立学校已经消亡，那么请等到她看看接下来会发生什么。</p><p><em>莱利女士是美国企业研究所的高级研究员。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 13 Aug 2023 19:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-death-of-public-school-review-find-a-place-to-learn-4817d47c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-death-of-public-school-review-find-a-place-to-learn-4817d47c<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>种族主义/仇外心理</category><category>学校</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>种族主义</category><category>仇外心理</category><category>学校</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Arts Calendar: Happenings for the Week of August 13]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一组 R 级《Strays》、《Billions》敲响了闭幕钟，乔恩·巴蒂斯特 (Jon Batiste) 在格莱美取得惊人成功后，带着新唱片回归。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000023001"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834482?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 《不羁之夜》中的场景</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：新线电影院</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000023001"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> 《华尔街日报》艺术评论人员</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 13 日上午 5:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-august-13-airdigital-62e842c2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><h3>电影</h3><p>• <strong>“蓝甲虫”</strong> <em>（8 月 18 日）</em> ：漫威可能是昆虫类英雄（蜘蛛侠、黑寡妇、蚁人和黄蜂女）中的蜂后，但 DC 也有自己的令人毛骨悚然的稳定 -爬行的角色。海梅·雷耶斯（由 Xolo Maridueña 饰演）成为了圣甲虫的宿主，圣甲虫是一种外星生物技术，将他变成了蓝甲虫。苏珊·萨兰登和乔治·洛佩兹是演员阵容中的大腕，其他演员还包括拉乌尔·马克斯·特鲁希略、布鲁纳·马尔克斯、达米安·阿尔卡扎、哈维·吉兰和阿德里安娜·巴拉扎。</p><p> • <strong>“Strays”</strong> <em>（8 月 18 日）</em> ：乔什·格林鲍姆 (Josh Greenbaum) 执导的这部不修边幅的真人电影，讲述了一个会说话的狗故事，试图教给旧的设置新的技巧，不适合幼犬。这部成人喜剧讲述了一只被遗弃的梗犬与一群流浪狗联手向虐待他的前主人复仇的故事。撇开古怪的前提不谈，演员阵容中充满了最佳表演水准的人才，如威尔·法瑞尔、杰米·福克斯、威尔·福特、兰德尔·帕克、罗布·里格尔、索菲亚·维加拉和丹尼斯·奎德。</p><p> • <strong>“月亮”</strong> <em><strong>&nbsp;</strong> (8 月 18 日)</em> : 凭借 2009 年影片《起飞》荣获韩国久负盛名的大钟导演奖的金容和 (Kim Yong-hwa) 带着一部讲述营救被困太空宇航员任务的生存剧回归。</p><p> • <strong>“诞生/重生”</strong> <em>（8 月 18 日）</em> ：这部独立恐怖电影由劳拉·莫斯 (Laura Moss) 执导，马林·爱尔兰 (Marin Ireland) 和朱迪·雷耶斯 (Judy Reyes) 主演，很大程度上借鉴了《弗兰肯斯坦》的风格，讲述了病理学家试图复活护士小女儿的故事女孩突然去世后。</p><p> • <strong>“西蒙娜：世纪女性”</strong> <em>（8 月 18 日）</em> ：奥利维尔·达汉 (Olivier Dahan) 编剧并执导了这部关于大屠杀幸存者、女权捍卫者和欧洲议会主席西蒙娜·维尔 (Simone Veil) 的法国传记片。艾尔莎·齐伯斯坦主演。</p><p> • <strong>《不羁之夜》</strong> <em>（纽约林肯中心上映，8 月 18 日至 24 日）</em> ：保罗·托马斯·安德森 (Paul Thomas Anderson) 的 70 年代末时期剧情片，二十五年前上映，由伯特·雷诺兹、马克·沃尔伯格、朱丽安·摩尔和菲利普·西摩主演霍夫曼着眼于加州成人电影世界的幽默和阴暗面。现在，影片的原始底片被放大到 70 毫米，并在纽约银幕上限量放映。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834474?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">林（由 Jolie Hoang-Rappaport 配音）和美猴王（吉米·欧阳饰）</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Netflix</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>电视</h3><p>• <strong>《Billions》第 7 季</strong><em>（Showtime，8 月 13 日）</em> ：在这部热门对冲基金电视剧的最后一季中，达米安·刘易斯 (Damian Lewis) 与大部分核心演员一起回归，饰演残酷的金融家鲍比·阿克塞尔罗德 (Bobby Axelrod)。对于那些无法忍受该系列结局的人来说，事情看起来很乐观：有四个“十亿”衍生作品正在制作中。</p><p> • <strong>《电话推销员》</strong> <em>（HBO，8 月 13 日）</em> ：HBO 的一部三集纪录片讲述了公民发展集团（Civic Development Group）两名斗志旺盛的员工长达数年的举报历程，该集团歪曲慈善事业，并在联邦调查后于 2010 年被罚款 1,880 万美元。我们的电视评论家<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/telemarketers-review-phony-phone-calls-hbo-29d70f21?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">称</a>该节目为“一部廉价、滑稽的杰作”。</p><p> • <strong>“重塑猫王：68 年回归”</strong> <em>（Paramount+，8 月 15 日）</em> ：这部长篇纪录片讲述了猫王的强力电视演唱会，这场演唱会让他在长期专注于电影之后重返现场表演。这部特别节目的导演史蒂夫·宾德（Steve Binder）在首播时吸引了近一半的电视观众观看，他是导演约翰·沙恩菲尔德 (John Scheinfeld) 的明星采访对象。</p>电影。<p></p><p> • <strong>“十年之战”</strong> <em>（美食网，8 月 16 日）</em> ：如果人们对某种食物有童年记忆，那么你很有可能知道他们是什么时候长大的。从 50 年代的明胶“沙拉”到 90 年代的水果卷，再到如今火爆的 TikTok 餐食，有些食物与特定的时代密不可分。这项烹饪比赛要求厨师们使用怀旧的小食和复古的设备来制作各种菜肴。</p><p> • <strong>“德普诉赫德”</strong> <em>（Netflix，8 月 16 日）</em> ：从法律角度来看，此案影响不大，但从文化角度来看，也许还没有诽谤审判引起如此轰动。艾玛·库珀这部由三部分组成的纪录片系列重新审视了法庭，重新审视了双方的证词，并探讨了导致诉讼过程中网络热潮的原因。</p><p> • <strong>“Harlan Coben&#39;s Shelter”</strong> <em>（Prime Video，8 月 17 日）</em> ：由同名作者创作的青少年犯罪惊悚片改编为八集，由 Jaden Michael 主演，饰演新泽西州一所学校的新生，他卷入了他的同学在处理家里的麻烦时失踪了，而他的妈妈（康斯坦斯·齐默扮演）则加剧了这些麻烦。</p><p> • <strong>《美猴王》</strong> <em>（Netflix，8 月 18 日）</em> ：在安东尼·斯塔奇 (Anthony Stacchi) 与吉米·欧阳 (Jimmy O. Yang)、鲍文·杨 (Bowen Yang)、BD Wong 和斯蒂芬妮·许 (Stephanie Hsu) 是配音演员之一。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834442?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">莱安农·吉登斯</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：埃布鲁·伊尔迪兹</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>音乐</h3><p>• <strong>Rhiannon Giddens，《You&#39;re the One》</strong> <em>（8 月 18 日）</em> ：今年 Ojai 音乐节总监发行了她的第三张专辑——六年来第一张个人唱片，也是她的第一首原创歌曲。这位普利策奖得主在 Jack Splash 制作的 LP 中的 12 首曲目中汲取了人们喜爱的民间音乐和流行音乐的元素。</p><p> • <strong>Cautious Clay，“KARPEH”</strong> <em>（8 月 18 日）</em> ：这位 R&amp;B 和独立艺术家（原名 Joshua Karpeh）在一张深具个人色彩的专辑中探索了他音乐的爵士乐基础，这是他的 Blue Note 首张专辑。专辑分为三个部分，讲述了他在俄亥俄州长大的生活，他努力摆脱家庭的努力，一路上的高潮和低谷，以及学习与自己和平相处的回报和困难。</p><p> • <strong>DeYarmond Edison，“Epoch”</strong> <em>（8 月 18 日）</em> ：大多数人都听说过 Bon Iver，Justin Vernon 备受推崇的独立项目。很少有人听说过德亚蒙德·爱迪生 (DeYarmond Edison)，他是 Bon Iver 的前身，该乐队由 Vernon 先生、Joe Westerlund、Phil Cook 和 Brad Cook（迷幻摇滚乐队 Megafaun 的最后三人）组成。新的盒装套装提供了该乐队的广阔视野，包括 83 张唱片，其中一些以前从未发行过。</p><p> • <strong>Hozier，“Unreal Unearth”</strong> <em>（8 月 18 日）</em> ：Hozier 2014 年的同名首张专辑大受欢迎，部分归功于单曲“Take Me to Church”，这让这位爱尔兰创作歌手看起来像是未来几年持续存在。 But his 2019 sophomore effort lacked its predecessor&#39;s popularity and it almost seemed as if he&#39;d disappeared from the scene entirely. He now returns with a 16-track LP, written during the Covid-19 pandemic, that is framed around Dante&#39;s “Inferno” and its nine circles of hell.</p><p> • <strong>Jon Batiste, “World Music Radio”</strong> <em>(Aug. 18)</em> : The jazz and R&amp;B musician—and longtime “Late Show” bandleader—had an impressive year at the Grammys, taking home five awards, including Album of the Year for “We Are.” He follows up that powerhouse showing with a 21-track, guest-filled record that includes appearances by NewJeans,</p> Lil Wayne, Lana Del Rey and more.<p></p><h3> Opera</h3><p> • <strong>“Così fan tutte”</strong> <em>(Kelowna Community Theatre, British Columbia, Aug. 18-19)</em> : Mozart&#39;s classic <em>opera buffa</em> gets a staging that updates its setting from 18th-century Naples to a 1930s resort in the Canadian Rockies. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="773" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834541?width=639&amp;height=773" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Dan McCarthy&#39;s &#39;Pink Pearl&#39; (2012)</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tripoli Gallery and Dan McCarthy</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>艺术</h3><p>• <strong>“A Magical Day at Ditch!”</strong> <em>(Tripoli Gallery, Wainscott, NY, Aug. 18-Sept. 18)</em> : As the end of summer appears just over the horizon, this presentation is a celebration of the season. Drawing its name from a surfers&#39; beach in Montauk, the sun-soaked show features work from Katherine Bernhardt (who curated the exhibition), Katherine Bradford, Yung Jake, Vaughn Davis Jr. , Dan McCarthy and others.</p><p> • <strong>“Ideas on Landscape”</strong> <em>(Tiger Strikes Asteroid, Chicago, Aug. 19-Sept. 30)</em> : Taking a classic theme—the landscape—and approaching it from the broadest possible angles, the artists in this show (a collaboration between the artist-run space in Chicago and SCOTTY, another artist-run gallery in Berlin) look to reinvent the subject while embracing its traditional roots. From stereoscopes to collages to sound recordings and beyond, a variety of media are deployed to explore the many meanings behind “landscape” in the contemporary world.</p><h3>其他</h3><p>• <strong>“The Texas Chain Saw Massacre”</strong> <em>(PC, Playstation 4 and 5, Xbox One and Series X/S, Aug. 18)</em> : Based on the cult horror franchise, this co-op and PvP (player versus player) game finds players searching for a character&#39;s sister while evading killers like Leatherface (played by Kane Hodder, a staple of the genre) and The Hitchhiker ( Edwin Neal, who played the same role in the 1974 film).</p><h3> Last Call</h3><p> • <strong>“The Doctor”</strong> <em>(Park Avenue Armory, New York, closes Aug. 19)</em> : Juliet Stevenson plays a stalwart physician whose life begins to crumble in Robert Icke&#39;s masterly and timely reimagining of a 1912 play by Arthur Schnitzler. In the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-doctor-review-complex-symptoms-of-a-moral-dilemma-c59fdcfe?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">words of our critic</a> , Ms. Stevenson “gives a performance of quiet but galvanizing intensity” in a work that highlights “how atomized and tribal contemporary society has become.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —For additional Arts Calendar listings visit wsj.com. Write to brian.kelly@wsj.com.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 13 Aug 2023 09:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-august-13-airdigital-62e842c2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-august-13-airdigital-62e842c2<category> arts in review</category><category>艺术</category><category>游戏</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>Music</category><category> Opera</category><category> Theater</category><category> Television/Radio</category><category> Calendar of Events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>IWE Filter</category><category> Routine General News</category><category> Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>游戏</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>音乐</category><category>歌剧</category><category>theater</category><category>电视</category><category>收音机</category><category>calendar of events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>iwe filter</category><category> routine general news </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Can San Francisco Save Itself From the Doom Loop?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>该市正在竞相为其市中心提出解决方案，该市中心因科技外流而空心化，并与无家可归和街头犯罪作斗争<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833049?width=1000&amp;height=562" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社；米凯拉·瓦切娃 (MICHAELA VATCHEVA) 为《华尔街日报》撰稿<span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128350"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128350"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jim-carlton" itemprop="url" rel="author">吉姆·卡尔顿</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/katherine-bindley" itemprop="url" rel="author">凯瑟琳·宾德利</a></span>Michaela Vatcheva 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated Aug. 13, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/san-francisco-crime-downtown-doom-loop-e5fcd7ba"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>当地领导人正在尽一切努力来维持旧金山陷入困境的市中心核心的运转，包括向退休的、手无寸铁的警察支付费用，让他们警惕麻烦。</p><p>其中一位是迈克·布朗 (Mike Browne)，他在旧金山当了 30 年警察，现在作为“社区大使”中队的一员在市中心巡逻，这些大使身穿蓝色衬衫，旨在帮助通勤者和购物者在旧金山<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-luxury-shopping-oasis-emerging-in-san-franciscos-struggling-downtown-35ad89e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">市中心商业区</a>及周边地区感到更安全<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-luxury-shopping-oasis-emerging-in-san-franciscos-struggling-downtown-35ad89e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">和购物区</a>。 Homelessness, drug use, and nonviolent crimes like shoplifting and car thefts are commonplace in many parts of the neighborhood.</p><p>最近，当一名明显精神错乱的男子撞到他时，布朗什么也没做。 “你会怎样做？”这位60岁的老人说道。 “你不能疯狂战斗。”</p><p>旧金山市中心在 2010 年代的繁荣很大程度上得益于科技行业的发展。 But those employees easily transitioned to remote work during the pandemic and the majority <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/san-francisco-commercial-real-estate-office-buildings-471742ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">never came back to the office</a> full time.去年，迫于削减成本的压力， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CRM" class="company-name">Salesforce</a>等科技巨头解雇了员工，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-lyft-salesforce-and-other-tech-firms-dump-office-space-as-they-downsize-11668477701?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">削减了在该市的房地产业务</a>。市中心许多办公楼的楼层现在空无一人。</p><p>这些变化与旧金山多年来不断恶化的一系列相互交织的问题相冲突，包括高昂的住房成本、街头无家可归、猖獗的财产犯罪、芬太尼危机以及大流行以来公共交通乘客量的急剧下降。</p><p> “我感觉不安全，到处都是流浪汉，到处都是垃圾，”63 岁的桑德拉·布里利 (Sandra Brealey) 说，她是一名长期居住在这座城市的居民，以前经常去市中心，但在过去五年里基本上不再去市中心了。年。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833040?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">旧金山警察局退休警官迈克尔·布朗（左）和迈克·莫兰（右）在担任安全大使期间离开梅西百货。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="810" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834445?width=1260&amp;height=810" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2023 年 5 月 11 日，无家可归者在美国音乐学院剧院门口睡觉。市中心及附近地区无家可归和吸毒现象仍然普遍存在。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Justin Sullivan/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>旧金山市中心现在的经济健康状况几乎落后于其他所有主要城市中心。 Its 25.7% office vacancy rate is close to 10 percentage points higher than the US vacancy rate of 16.4%, according to commercial real-estate firm <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CIGI" class="">Colliers International</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span>乘坐湾区快速交通列车前往市中心的乘客量是 2019 年水平的三分之一。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JWN" class="company-name">Nordstrom</a>和 Banana Republic 等零售商在过去几个月宣布将关闭旧金山市中心的商店。位于市中心的该市最大购物中心的所有者正在将其返还给贷方，而不是继续偿还债务。</p><p>旧金山的其他地区正在从大流行病的低迷中更快地恢复，餐馆和商店都人满为患。 But downtown has long been the economic engine of this city of 808,000, generating three quarters of the local gross domestic product. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="850" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834721?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>市政府官员表示，社区大使并不是解决市中心困境的解决方案，而是旨在防止该地区进一步恶化并进入经济学家所说的“末日循环”的几种创可贴之一。</p><p>城市末日循环始于与核心产业相关的触发事件，例如 20 世纪 70 年代制造业工作开始离开底特律。税收减少，服务受到影响，企业倒闭，混乱开始蔓延。居民离开，通勤者和购物者远离，这个循环自我强化。</p><p>对于旧金山市中心出现厄运循环的可能性有多大以及何时开始，经济学家们有不同的看法，但大多数人都认为需要做出重大改变来恢复社区的健康。</p><p> “San Francisco is one of the cities I&#39;d worry about the most,” said Arpit Gupta, an associate professor at New York University&#39;s Stern School of Business who has studied urban doom loops. “触发效应就在那里。”</p><h3>独特的脆弱性</h3><p>经济学家表示，旧金山比大多数其他城市更容易受到这一流行病的影响。近几十年来，它不断增加就业岗位，却没有与之相匹配的住房，它的劳动力只剩下两个相对没有吸引力的选择：在住房上花费大量资金，或者搬到更远的地方并忍受长时间的通勤。</p><p>随着大流行的发生，情况发生了变化。许多工人发现他们不需要支付旧金山的生活费，也不需要忍受旧金山的问题就能完成工作。 2020年至2022年间，该市人口下降7.5%，是美国人口超过5万的城市中下降幅度最大的。</p><p>据 CBRE 称，旧金山的科技公司目前占市中心可用转租空间的 76%。根据数据公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSGP" class="">CoStar</a>的数据，在疫情期间，Salesforce 将市中心的房地产足迹减少了 60% 以上<span class="company-name-type">。</span> Meta 的空间减少了 36%。</p><h4>金融区</h4><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/fader/0b35014c-6a2c-4990-8d27-e7f12c3b6f64.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>没有所有这些工人回来已经在市中心产生了连锁反应。</p><p> Jack&#39;s Shoe Repair Service 位于地铁出口前，那里曾经是大批通勤者经过的地方，店主 Setrak Soghomonian 表示，该店的业务量仅恢复了疫情前的 40% 左右。 Jack&#39;s used to employ three full-time employees, but is now down to just one.</p><p> “只有当游客到来时，情况才会好转，”索格莫尼安说。 “普通人已经不在了。”</p><p>尽管旧金山正在全市范围内增加就业机会，但市中心的经济放缓影响了其税收收入。 The city controller&#39;s office anticipates that revenue will rise 0.6% in the current fiscal year and 3.3% next fiscal year. 2018-19 财年，收入增长近 20%。上一财年增长了 7.9%。</p><p>无家可归和吸毒现象在市中心及其附近仍然普遍存在。事实证明，让无家可归者离开街道是很困难的，因为经济适用房长期短缺，而且联邦法院的命令使得很难违背他们的意愿将他们驱逐出去。</p><p>警察和大使部署最密集的地区是市中心的联合广场购物区。商家和购物者表示，入店行窃和骚扰行为因此减少。</p><p>但上班族仍然抱怨街头和地铁站的手机盗窃等犯罪行为。在毗邻市中心购物区的田德隆区，有开放的毒品市场。</p><p> Though San Francisco&#39;s homicide rate is relatively low compared with other major cities, its property crime rates are among the highest. In the central police district that includes downtown, car break-ins rose 171% in 2021, 2% last year, and 3% in the first half of 2023, compared with the prior year periods.截至今年 6 月，入室盗窃案增加了 14%。</p><p> “合同是，你提供一个安全的做生意的地方，我提供税收，”前科技工作者、现在在一家名为 GrowSF 的非营利组织工作的史蒂文·巴斯 (Steven Buss) 说。 “在我们能够提供一个安全的做生意场所之前，我不知道企业是否会回来。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834444?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">金融区的 Wayfare Tavern。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833042?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">市场街上一家关门的商店。</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>人工智能的希望</h3><p>一些人认为人工智能公司将通过推动该地区的下一次科技繁荣来帮助旧金山市中心避免末日循环。</p><p>几家最有价值的人工智能公司，例如 ChatGPT 的开发商 OpenAI，都总部位于这里。 OpenAI 最近搬进了 Mission 区 60,000 平方英尺的办公空间，另一家人工智能公司 Hive 正在转租市中心一座建筑的三层楼。</p><p> “在世界其他任何地方，你都无法真正达到建立人工智能初创公司所需的速度和规模，”专注于人工智能领域的 Bloomberg Beta 投资者 Amber Yang 表示。</p><p>据世邦魏理仕称，今年第二季度旧金山租用或续租的 450 万平方英尺办公空间租户中，人工智能公司占近 18%。</p><p>但据高力国际称，人工智能行业还需要数年时间才能拥有足够大的公司，从而对旧金山的办公市场产生重大影响，旧金山的办公楼市场估计有 2500 万平方英尺的空置空间。</p><p>活跃于城市政治的企业家比拉尔·马哈茂德 (Bilal Mahmood) 表示：“即使拥有 500 家初创公司，也不等于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ABNB" class="">Airbnb</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DBX" class="">Dropbox</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span> Facebook、Google 拥有了数千名员工。”</p><p>他正在组织努力将一所大学校园迁至市中心，部分原因是他不希望旧金山在收入方面过于依赖某一行业，就像以前对互联网公司所做的那样。</p><p>城市领导人的另一个想法是通过用居民取代商业来使旧金山市中心更加活跃。该市已通过立法，使办公室改建为住宅变得更加容易。</p><h4><strong>内河码头</strong></h4><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/fader/851ad8c4-0387-49e3-9768-b650addde5a8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Rich Hillis, San Francisco&#39;s planning director, said around 5 million square feet of office real estate downtown, less than a fifth of what is currently vacant, could be converted to apartments or condominiums.</p><p> In one of the first projects, Singular Builders hopes to begin work this fall on conversion of five floors of offices into 40 apartments atop a historic building constructed in 1908, said chief executive Jeff Gherardini.</p><p>但盖拉迪尼理解为什么潜在居民可能会持谨慎态度。他最近走进旧金山郊区的一家咖啡店，看到一名男子在背包里塞满了偷来的商品。 “我对此感到厌倦，”他说。</p><h3> “空虚到充满活力”</h3><p>由于大流行病和乔治·弗洛伊德被杀后的抗议活动以来退休人数增加和招募困难，旧金山是众多警察短缺的城市之一，但其 27% 的短缺尤其严重。</p><p>伦敦市长伦敦·布里德 (London Breed) 将警察加班预算增加了 2500 万美元，试图弥补原定 2,182 名警员中 599 名警员的缺口。</p><p>布里德在接受采访时表示，市中心正在改善，街道变得更加干净，她希望尽快让更多的人在那里工作和购物。一项名为“空置到充满活力”的计划旨在用具有相似主题（例如食品准备或艺术）的企业来填补空置的店面。</p><p>这位民主党市长表示：“我们必须把重点放在第一位，公共安全，第二位……以推动商业回到旧金山。”</p><p>她说，与此同时，社区大使正在帮助弥补差额。 “我想做一些事情，让具有执法专业知识的人成为街上的眼睛和耳朵，”布里德说。</p><p>该计划于 2020 年与包括 Browne 在内的 8 名前警察一起启动。现在全市有 74 名警官配备了警用无线电。</p><p>两年前，布朗和他的搭档迈克·莫兰在联合广场发现四名青少年在袭击一对老年夫妇并抢走他们的财物后沿着街道奔跑。他们用无线电报告了这一犯罪事件，几分钟之内，四人中的三人就被穿制服的警察逮捕了。</p><p> “否则他们不可能这么快到达那里，”65 岁的退休警察队长莫兰说。</p><p> San Francisco is looking to hire another 25 ambassadors by the end of the year, as it also seeks to recruit more officers.</p><p> “这是整体解决方案吗？我不这么认为，”中士说。威尔·埃利夫（Will Elieff）负责监督中队。 “该部门正在将此视为解决方案的一部分。”</p><h3> 《我心科幻》</h3><p>今年旧金山经济最有希望的迹象之一是旅游业。官员们预计，今年将有 2390 万人次到访，高于 2022 年的 2190 万人次。尽管这一数字仍低于 2019 年 2500 万人次游客峰值，但酒店入住率已从疫情期间的 8% 低点反弹至 60%。旧金山酒店理事会。疫情爆发前，酒店已入住 80%。</p><p> John&#39;s Grill 是一家拥有 115 年历史的市中心餐厅，店主 John Konstin 表示，从 2019 年开始，今年的收入有望增长 20%。他将其归功于旅游业和更多的企业支出。 “公司又开始娱乐了，”康斯汀先生说。</p><p> There are also signs of increased demand for office space, with jumps in the past quarter in prospective tenants looking to lease, according to real-estate brokers.办公室工作人员表示，过去几个月里，他们大楼周围的街道看起来更干净了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833041?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">游客在旧金山联合广场拍照。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833043?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">缆车停在鲍威尔街。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>许多城市领导人指出，旧金山成功地从其他经济衰退中恢复过来，例如 2000 年互联网泡沫破灭和 1906 年地震。</p><p>但在更多人开始在市中心工作和购物之前，该地区仍面临进入末日循环的风险。</p><p>市政府办公室在 7 月份的月度报告中发现，尽管该市其他大多数地方都出现强劲增长，但市中心写字楼市场几乎没有复苏的迹象。报告称，市中心的租金、办公室出勤率和交通乘客量基本持平。</p><p>一群当地慈善家正在尝试一种新策略：广告。</p><p>他们正在发起一项新的公民自豪感运动，以“我爱纽约”为蓝本，但旨在保留现有企业，吸引新企业，并改变对该城市的负面叙述。它将包括旧金山周围、商店和公交车站的广告和实物展示。</p><p> “San Francisco in the past has been a bit arrogant about its position in the world both economically and culturally,” said Dan Kingsley, a commercial real-estate developer involved with the project. “没有太多的自我推销，这一点需要改变。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Peter Grant 和 Zusha Elinson 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给吉姆·卡尔顿（Jim Carlton）（ <a href="mailto:Jim.Carlton@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jim.Carlton@wsj.com）</a>和凯瑟琳·宾德利（Katherine Bindley）（ <a href="mailto:katie.bindley@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">katie.bindley@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 13 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/san-francisco-crime-downtown-doom-loop-e5fcd7ba</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/san-francisco-crime-downtown-doom-loop-e5fcd7ba<author><![CDATA[Jim CarltonKatherine Bindley]]></author><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>领导者</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>无家可归</category><category>住房问题</category><category>社会问题</category><category>入室盗窃/盗窃</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>无家可归</category><category>住房问题</category><category>社会问题</category><category>盗窃</category><category>盗窃</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Canova: Sketching in Clay’ Review: Sculptures in the Rough]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> An exhibition at the National Gallery of Art surveys the expressive preparatory studies that Antonio Canova, the most famous European artist of the pre-Romantic era, made for his meticulous marble masterworks. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12410125361470374628104590072221907021264"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833854?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Adam and Eve Mourning the Dead Abel&#39; (c. 1818-22)</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Museo Gypsotheca Antonio Canova, Possagno </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12410125361470374628104590072221907021264"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Karen Wilkin</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 12, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canova-sketching-in-clay-review-sculptures-in-the-rough-national-gallery-of-art-34622cd7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><em>华盛顿</em></p><p>Around 1800, the sculptor of choice for ambitious collectors was the Italian virtuoso Antonio Canova (1757-1822), acclaimed as the greatest carver of marble since Phidias. His works were eagerly acquired by the rich and powerful, including Napoleon and his family, European nobility and British aristocrats; a portrait by Canova equaled status. Recognized early, he received his first public commission—a funerary monument for Pope Clement XIV in Santi Apostoli, Rome—in 1783 at age 26. Pope Clement XIII&#39;s funerary monument in St. Peter&#39;s soon followed, as well as a memorial to Titian, for the Frari, in Venice (unrealized, but the design was later adapted for the tomb of the Austrian Archduchess Maria Christina, in Vienna), and a life-size <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canovas-george-washington-review-the-very-model-of-a-lost-masterpiece-1528542000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">portrait of George Washington,</a> as a Roman senator, for the North Carolina State House. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>Canova: Sketching in Clay</strong></p><p> <em>National Gallery of Art, through Oct. 9</em></p></div></div><p> Canova&#39;s name is inextricable from sleek marble statues that define Neo-Classicism by updating Greek sculpture of the Golden Age. Animated by his ability to turn stone into evocations of transparent fabric, smooth flesh and twining hair, they nevertheless remain reticent and cool. Yet anyone who has visited the Museo Gypsotheca Antonio Canova, the museum established in the sculptor&#39;s honor by his stepbrother, in Possagno, his Veneto birthplace, has encountered another Canova: the author of impassioned <em>bozzetti</em> (sketches) in responsive, malleable clay. These lively works, made not for exhibition, but to probe ideas, embody his first thoughts about a subject. (Fired to stabilize the clay, they become terracotta—literally “cooked earth.”)</p><p> “Canova: Sketching in Clay,” at the National Gallery of Art, assembles about 30 of these intimate, expressive studies, plus several more finished terracotta portraits, along with larger plasters that were the next stage in developing the marbles, and a few of the suave stone sculptures that established and sustained the artist&#39;s international reputation. Jointly organized by the National Gallery and the Art Institute of Chicago, the exhibition is curated by the National Gallery&#39;s CD Dickerson III and Chicago&#39;s Emerson Bowyer. It is accompanied by a comprehensive, beautifully illustrated catalog, the first monograph devoted to the clay works, that also details Canova&#39;s process. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="858" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833851?width=639&amp;height=858" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Immaculate Virgin&#39; (c. 1818-22)</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Museo Gypsotheca Antonio Canova, Possagno</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Divided into three thematic sections—“Portraiture,” “Myths and Legends” and “Monuments and Faith”—the exhibition is fascinating, illuminating and exhilarating. The rough, nervous but wholly convincing bozzetti capture the speed and intensity with which Canova modeled them; we follow the thrusts and swipes of his tools and the insistent pressure of his fingers as he pressed on balls of clay. At the start, his working method is revealed, from bozzetto to life-size marble, by a seated portrait of Napoleon&#39;s mother. (Unlike Napoleon&#39;s sister Pauline, in Canova&#39;s celebrated reclining portrait in the Villa Borghese, Rome, Madame Mère— Letizia Ramolino Bonaparte —is fully clothed.) We see Canova changing the position of an arm and varying the drapery in speedily modeled clay, without any attempt at likeness. The plaster version, cast from a clay model twice the size of the sketch, retains the generic Neo-Classical head, above a figure wrapped in voluptuous cloth, but the marble (made by Canova&#39;s assistants, with details and surface nuances carved by him) gives us a distinct individual, an older woman with a double chin, in the guise of a Roman matron. The entire process, including casting in plaster and scaling-up to marble, is recapitulated in an accompanying video.</p><p> The terracottas range from expediently modeled sketches that appear to test possibilities at high speed, as if Canova&#39;s ideas were outracing his hand, to more finished, perhaps final conceptions of ideas. While the delicacy of modeling and drapery in the refined bozzetti is admirable, the most urgent, roughest little sculptures—especially the groups of multiple figures—are, to my eye, the most compelling. The meticulousness of the fine vertical striations of the “Immaculate Virgin” (c. 1818-22) makes them read like a metaphor for untouchable purity, but the terracottas I would most like to live with are three wrenching versions of “Adam and Eve Mourning the Dead Abel” (c. 1818-22). </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-slideshow"><div class="strap-container"><h3 class="wsj-slideshow-title strap"> <a href="">Sculptures in the Rough</a></h3><h4 class="wsj-media-dek sub-strap"> Canova: Sketching in Clay </h4></div><div class="wsj-slideshow-wrap"><amp-carousel layout="responsive" height="400" width="600" type="slides" controls=""><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834376/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-834376/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-834376/"> &#39;Muse of Lyric Poetry&#39; (c. 1814-16), Antonio Canova <span class="imageCredit">The Cleveland Museum of Art</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834375/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-834375/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-834375/"> &#39;Pope Clement XIV&#39; (1783), Antonio Canova <span class="imageCredit">Museo Gypsotheca Antonio Canova, Possagno</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834374/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-834374/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-834374/"> &#39;Satyr and a Nymph&#39; (c. 1786-87), Antonio Canova <span class="imageCredit">Museo Gypsotheca Antonio Canova, Possagno</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834373/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-834373/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-834373/"> &#39;Pyrrhus Sacrificing Polyxena&#39; (c. 1798-99), Antonio Canova <span class="imageCredit">Museo Gypsotheca Antonio Canova, Possagno</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834372/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-834372/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-834372/"> &#39;Religion&#39; (c. 1786-87), Antonio Canova <span class="imageCredit">Galleria dell&#39;Accademia Tadini, Lovere</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834371/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-834371/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-834371/"> &#39;The Three Graces&#39; (1812), Antonio Canova <span class="imageCredit">Musee des Beaux-Arts de Lyon</span></p></div></amp-carousel></div></div></div><p> Like the “Immaculate Virgin,” they are thought to be studies for works intended for the memorial church Canova planned for himself—the chilly, monumental Tempio Canoviano, in Possagno, designed by the artist and completed after his death. Each bozzetto is a broad-based pyramid, with Adam and Eve framing their supine son. In the most poignant, Eve bends to touch her cheek to Abel&#39;s, his head cradled in her lap. Adam throws his head back in anguish. A few fierce stabs of the modeling tool turn a blob of clay into the tortured head of a devastated father. The eloquent little sculpture seems to take shape as we watch, inert clay magically becoming musculature, hair and agonized expressions, while somehow retaining its identity as a primordial lump.</p><p> The exquisite marble “Terpsichore Lyran (Muse of Lyric Poetry)” (c. 1814-16), also in the show, presents the Canova we know, with its transparent drapery and incredibly subtle modulations of form. I&#39;d love to have seen the bozzetto.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ms. Wilkin is an independent curator and critic.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canova-sketching-in-clay-review-sculptures-in-the-rough-national-gallery-of-art-34622cd7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canova-sketching-in-clay-review-sculptures-in-the-rough-national-gallery-of-art-34622cd7<category> arts in review</category><category> Entertainment Venues</category><category> Museums/Galleries/Gardens</category><category> Leisure/Arts/Hospitality</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>entertainment venues</category><category> museums</category><category> galleries</category><category> gardens</category><category> leisure</category><category> hospitality</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Zelig’: Woody Allen as No One and Everyone]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Released 40 years ago, the writer-director&#39;s film blends archival footage from the 1920s with new material filmed to look like old newsreels to construct a mockumentary about conformity that speaks to our time. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136172594871364"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832419?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mia Farrow and Woody Allen in &#39;Zelig&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Orion/Warner Bros/Kobal/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136172594871364"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Peter Tonguette</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 5:37 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/zelig-woody-allen-as-no-one-and-everyone-3fbc16bc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <strong>For most of his career</strong> , Woody Allen has been consistently associated with a certain species of romantic comedy. In such widely popular films as “ Annie Hall ” and “Hannah and Her Sisters,” Mr. Allen offered comic sketches of the amorous affairs of late-20th-century Manhattanites. Each relied on what came to be viewed as a formula: verbal banter, cultural erudition, visual elegance and, of course, the filmmaker&#39;s own on-screen persona of a talkative worrywart.</p><p> Yet the 87-year-old writer-director&#39;s career is lined with surprising detours. He has directed in the tradition of German Expressionism (“Shadows and Fog”), Anton Chekhov (“September”) and American musical comedy (“Everyone Says I Love You”); two of his best films, “Match Point” and “Cassandra&#39;s Dream,” are murder stories.</p><p> Undoubtedly Mr. Allen&#39;s boldest, most unexpected achievement is his 1983 film “Zelig.” The fictional, documentary-style film purports to recount the enigmatic life of a figure from the Jazz Age, Leonard Zelig. Played by an especially meek and shrinking Mr. Allen, Zelig possesses an instinct for conformity so profound that he proves capable of both maneuvering himself into unlikely settings and undergoing physical metamorphoses to suit each occasion. Depending on who is standing beside him, Zelig adopts guises ranging from doctor to gangster to aristocrat. Ironically, the character&#39;s cipher-like quality results in widespread renown.</p><p> The premise is beyond fantastic; one sequence depicts Zelig, in an act of psychosomatic conformity, swelling to a great weight while in the proximity of two obese men. Nonetheless, Mr. Allen saw the story as a chance to make serious points about the risk that social pressures pose to individuality—“the specific danger of abandoning one&#39;s own true self, in an effort to be liked, not to make trouble, to fit in,” as the filmmaker explained to interviewer Stig Björkman in the book “Woody Allen on Woody Allen.”</p><p> Perhaps to underscore the seriousness of his intentions, Mr. Allen decided against presenting the story of the so-called human chameleon in traditional dramatic scenes. Instead, the filmmaker adopted a documentary format in which a solemn narrator (the voice of Patrick Horgan ) guides the viewer through archival footage of cityscapes, nightclub life and dancing flappers, all of which effortlessly kindles the atmosphere of the Jazz Age.</p><p> Then, with cinematographer Gordon Willis, Mr. Allen shot footage of himself and other actors—including Mia Farrow as Zelig&#39;s psychiatrist, confidante and eventual lover, Eudora Fletcher —in the same shaky and grainy manner of the old footage.</p><p> Film editor Susan E. Morse gracefully stitched together old and new material to create a latticework of real and simulated newsreel-style footage, photographs and &#39;20s-era music. Ms. Morse also judiciously placed Mr. Allen within extant footage so that the character of Zelig could occasionally appear to share the same frame as various notables, including Babe Ruth.</p><p> Adding to the film&#39;s patina of reality, Mr. Allen filmed interviews with public intellectuals who soberly ruminate on Zelig&#39;s significance, including Saul Bellow, Irving Howe and Susan Sontag. “He was the phenomenon of the &#39;20s,” Ms. Sontag says in a spot-on send-up of breathless talking-head commentaries. “When you think that, at that time, he was as well-known as Lindbergh, it&#39;s really quite astonishing.” Mr. Allen&#39;s astonishingly accurate simulacrum of a documentary will be recognized by anyone who has ever watched such programming on public television.</p><p> What this adds up to is far more than a mere technical feat (though it is that—Willis was nominated for an Oscar for his cinematography). Through its elaborate bricolage, the film offers a profound commentary on an individual reacting to the expectations, orthodoxies and subtly coercive forces of modern society. Although Zelig internalized these pressures to an extreme, absurd degree, each of us can identify with the source of his anxiety: the wanting to belong, the desire to say the right thing, the succor that can come from being among a crowd and the wish to bask in the reflected glory of celebrity. Even the film&#39;s faux-documentary style reflects Zelig&#39;s true nature; because we perceive the character as a distant figure glimpsed in purportedly old clips and fuzzy stills, he comes across not so much as a fully rounded human being than<strong></strong> as a nonentity among the horde—which is exactly what he is.</p><p> “It&#39;s safe to be like the others,” Zelig admits under hypnosis during one of his sessions with Dr. Fletcher. He also reveals the origins of his compulsion to emulate others to be rather ordinary: He suggests that his entire shape-shifting condition springs from the shame he once felt for being the only person in a group not to have read “Moby-Dick.” How many of us might be tempted to dissimulate when it would mean appearing smarter, more literate or more cosmopolitan?</p><p> Forty years after its release, “Zelig” increasingly looks less like a re-creation of a past time than a parable for the present, when the pressure to swim with the tide is more keenly felt than ever.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Tonguette is the author of “Picturing Peter Bogdanovich : My Conversations With the New Hollywood Director.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 21:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/zelig-woody-allen-as-no-one-and-everyone-3fbc16bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/zelig-woody-allen-as-no-one-and-everyone-3fbc16bc<category> arts in review</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>Commentaries/Opinions</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>commentaries</category><category> opinions</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[15 Books We Read This Week]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> George Orwell&#39;s marriage, the unlikely life of an early Hollywood star, the man who changed American folk music and more. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000022636"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
